  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Advocacy for Buddhist Religious Leaders to raise awareness on gender equality</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to promote awareness and advocacy from Buddhist Religious leaders, monastic school teachers and students on gender equality and women&#x2019;s rights. Thingaha will support the teachers and students to design an education curriculum based on local stories and experiences of inequality and injustice and will conduct advocacy activities together with them in order to get Monks and Nuns involved. Buddhist religious leaders are potential agents for positive change within their sphere of influence, and Thingaha will try to engage them in promoting safe spaces for all (men and women) despite their ethnicity or faith group. Safe spaces refer to places where there is no misuse of power and/or use of violence. This is important as Monastic Schools are institutions where the most poor and marginalized can access to education. This project will be conducted in 12 schools in 5 areas in total: Yangon, Sagaing, Magwei, Bago regions and Mon state. 

For this project, Thingaha will conduct a research and assessment phase first to be able to design jointly the draft curriculum and to adapt it to the different contexts and realities. After this first phase they will share the material with monastic school teachers and students and will advocate to Monks and Nuns as well as faith based organizations in order to integrate this in their teaching methodologies. The project seeks to create a person-to-person chain reaction of change in attitudes and behaviours on a scale sufficient to generate a mass awareness and prevention mechanisms in communities to create safe spaces for all.</narrative>
  </description>
